Lab 5: Exploring Bus Stop Placement in Santa Barbara¶

Introduction: In this lab, we delve into the intricate process of evaluating bus stop locations along Bus 11 in Santa Barbara.
Public transportation plays a pivotal role in urban mobility, and strategically placing bus stops can significantly enhance accessibility and efficiency.
Through the utilization of spatial optimization techniques, we aim to evaluate bus stops, considering factors such as proximity to residential areas and population density.

By leveraging geographic information systems (GIS) and mathematical modeling, we seek to find a balance between the number of bus stops and the average travel distance for residents.
Through this exploration, we can gain valuable insights into enhancing public transportation systems while addressing urban mobility challenges.

import folium

route_midpoint = route_11_.iloc[0].geometry.interpolate(0.5, normalized=True)
m = folium.Map(location=[route_midpoint.y, route_midpoint.x], zoom_start=13)

for idx, row in stops_.iterrows():
    folium.Marker(
        location=[row.geometry.y, row.geometry.x],
        popup=row['name'],
        icon=folium.Icon(color='pink')
    ).add_to(m)

folium.PolyLine(
    locations=[(coord[1], coord[0]) for coord in route_11_.iloc[0].geometry.coords],
    color='blue',
    weight=5,
    opacity=0.8
).add_to(m)

m.save('map.html')

Task: Split each row in the multiline string stops_11 using the .split() method and update the variable stops_11.¶

Things to Note:

  • The .split() method splits the input string based on a specified delimiter and returns a list of the splitted elements.
  • By default, the .split() method uses the space character (" ") as the delimiter.
  • You can specify a different delimiter, "\n", as an argument to the .split() method.
    • \n indicates an enter (breakline)
In [347]:
text = "Hello world! Welcome to Python programming!"

print(words)

Question 3: Match each stop name in stops_11 with corresponding rows in the stops GeoDataFrame. (3 pts)¶

Things to Check: (2 pt)

  • Initialize an empty list, geoms, to store the geometries of corresponding stops for each stop name in stops_11.
  • Use a for loop to iterate through each element in stops_11 with its index, i.
  • Utilize DataFrame['Column'].str.contains('String') to check if any stop names in the stops GeoDataFrame contain each stop name in stops_11.
    • The .contains() method returns True or False based on whether each column value contains the specified string or not.
  • Identify a new variable, matched_stops using the .loc function and .str.contains() method.
  • Append the unary union of the matched_stops to the geoms list.
  • If the length of matched_stops is zero, print out the index i and the corresponding stops_11 element to identify unmatched stops for correction.

Things to Double-Check: (1 pts)

  • There must be unmatched stop names in stops_11.
    • Refer to the Folium map created for Question 1 and the order of the original stop_11 string.
    • By clicking on the stop points in the Folium map, determine the stop names in order.
    • Update the stop names in stops_11 by modifying the list elements.
    • Rerun the cell for the matching process.
In [359]:
geoms = []

for i, stop_name in enumerate(stops_11):
    matched_stops = stops.loc[stops['name'].str.contains(stop_name, case=False, na=False)]
    
    if len(matched_stops) > 0:
        geoms.append(matched_stops.unary_union)

    else:
        print(f"No matches found for stop name at index {i}: {stop_name}")

Task: Take a subset of blocks within S distance from the stops on Bus 11.¶

Optimization Model for Reducing Bus Stops on Bus 11 in Santa Barbara¶

The following model is designed to minimize the overall distance that passengers need to walk to reach a bus stop, while ensuring a predetermined number of stops are selected and every passenger is assigned to a selected bus stop.
This model aims to minimize the total weighted distance passengers need to travel to reach their assigned bus stops.
The objective function sums up the product of demand $a_i$ at each location $i$ and the distance $D_{ij}$ to each bus stop $j$, multiplied by the assignment variable $Z_{ij}$.
The constraints ensure that every location is assigned to exactly one bus stop, a fixed number of bus stops are selected, and locations are only assigned to selected bus stops.
This model is particularly useful for urban planning and public transportation optimization, ensuring efficient and effective bus stop placement while considering passenger convenience.

  • $a_i$ represents the demand at location $i$ (e.g., number of passengers).
  • $D_{ij}$ is the distance between location $i$ and bus stop $j$.
  • $Z_{ij}$ is a binary variable indicating if location $i$ is assigned to bus stop $j$ (1 if assigned, 0 otherwise).
  • $P$ is the predetermined number of bus stops to be selected.
  • $S$ represents the coverage distance standard
  • $N_i$ is the set of bus stops that are within $S$ distance for location $i$.

Objective Function¶

$ \text{Minimize} \sum_{i} \sum_{j} a_i D_{ij} Z_{ij} $

Constraints¶

  1. Assignment Constraint:

$ \sum_{j \in N_i} Z_{ij} = 1 \quad \forall i $

This ensures that each location $i$ is assigned to exactly one bus stop $j$.

  1. Bus Stop Selection Constraint:

$ \sum_{j} X_j = P $

Here, $X_j$ is a binary variable indicating if bus stop $j$ is selected (1 if selected, 0 otherwise), and $P$ is the predetermined number of bus stops to be selected.

  1. Assignment and Selection Relationship:

$ Z_{ij} \leq X_j \quad \forall i, j $

This ensures that location $i$ can only be assigned to bus stop $j$ if bus stop $j$ is selected.

Question 4: Try different P values to solve the model. Report what values make the model infeasible, and explain the reason why. ( 2 pts )¶

Put your ANSWER in this markdown cell¶

... The model is feasible for a value of P = 10, meaning that the blocks are able to be covered bvy (52-P=) 42 bus stops rather than the current 52 stops. However, when P is increased to P = 11 and we try to run the model limiting the number of bus stops to (52-11=) 41 bus stops, the model is infeasible. This indicates that 42 bus stops is the minimum number of stops that can support the 296 blocks at an efficient rate. When the number of stops is reduced to 41, the model is infeasible and the transit system loses efficiency. ...

Question 5: Construct a model for Bus Stop Selection. ( 3 pts )¶

  • Correctly defined decision variables (1 pt)
  • Correctly defined objective function (0.5 pts)
  • Correctly defined constraints (1.5 pts)
In [380]:
# Create a new model
m = gp.Model("Bus Stop Selection")

# Create variables
Z_ij = m.addVars(I, J, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name="Z_ij")
X_j = m.addVars(J, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name="X_j")

# Set objective
m.setObjective(gp.quicksum(gp.quicksum(a_i[i] * D_ij[i][j] * Z_ij[i,j] for j in range (J)) for i in range (I)), gp.GRB.MINIMIZE)

# Add constraints
# Constraint 1: \sum_{j \in N_i} Z_{ij} = 1 ∀i
m.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(Z_ij[i,j] for j in N_i[i]) == 1 for i in range (I))
    
# Constraint 2: \sum_{j} X_j = P
m.addConstr(gp.quicksum(X_j[j] for j in range(J)) == P)

# Constraint 3: Z_{ij} <= X_j ∀i, j
m.addConstrs(Z_ij[i,j] <= X_j[j] for i in range(I) for j in range (J))

# Optimize model
m.optimize()

Question 6: Draw a linestring between each block to a bus stop it's assigned to. ( 2 pts )¶

  • Collect the linestrings into a variable, Z_lines.
  • Use a for loop to iterate through each block, indexed as i.
  • Iterate through each bus stop, indexed as j, and check if the Z_ij value is greater than 0.5.
    • If the model is solved correctly, for each i, only one j will have a Z_ij value greater than 0.5.
  • Find the nearest point between block i and bus stop j, as a bus stop j can be a MultiPoint.
    • Utilize the nearest_points() function from shapely.ops.
    • Refer to the documentation page for further information.
  • Connect the nearest point to block i and create a linestring.

Question 7: Create a function that solves a model and displays the output. ( 2 pts )¶

  • The function will take one argument, P, indicating the number of bus stations to retain. (0.5 pts)
  • It will solve the optimization model with the given P.
  • The function will generate selected_stops, unselected_stops, and Z_lines based on the model output.
  • It will display a figure showing selected_stops, unselected_stops, blocks, and Z_lines. (0.5 pts)
  • The function will return three values: selected_stops, Z_lines, and the objective value of the model. (1 pt)
In [391]:
def solve_m(P):
    P = P
    # Create a new model
    m = gp.Model("Bus Stop Selection")

    # Create variables
    Z_ij = m.addVars(I, J, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name="Z_ij")
    X_j = m.addVars(J, vtype=GRB.BINARY, name="X_j")

    # Set objective
    m.setObjective(gp.quicksum(gp.quicksum(a_i[i] * D_ij[i][j] * Z_ij[i,j] for j in range (J)) for i in range (I)), gp.GRB.MINIMIZE)

    # Add constraints
    # Constraint 1: \sum_{j \in N_i} Z_{ij} = 1 ∀i
    m.addConstrs(gp.quicksum(Z_ij[i,j] for j in N_i[i]) == 1 for i in range (I))
    
    # Constraint 2: \sum_{j} X_j = P
    m.addConstr(gp.quicksum(X_j[j] for j in range(J)) == P)

    # Constraint 3: Z_{ij} <= X_j ∀i, j
    m.addConstrs(Z_ij[i,j] <= X_j[j] for i in range(I) for j in range (J))

    # Optimize model
    m.optimize()
    selected_stops = fin_stops.loc[[X_j[j].x > 0.5 for j in range(J)]]
    unselected_stops = fin_stops.drop(selected_stops.index)
    from shapely.ops import nearest_points
    from shapely.geometry import LineString

    Z_lines = []

    for i in range(I):
        for j in range(J):
            if Z_ij[i, j].X > 0.5:  
                Z_lines.append(LineString(nearest_points(blocks.centroid[i], fin_stops.geometry[j])))

    # Create lists for selected and unselected stops
    selected_stops = []
    unselected_stops = []

    for j in range(J):
        if X_j[j].X > 0.5:
            selected_stops.append(fin_stops.geometry.iloc[j])
        else:
            unselected_stops.append(fin_stops.geometry.iloc[j])

    # Convert the lists to GeoSeries
    selected_stops = gpd.GeoSeries(selected_stops)
    unselected_stops = gpd.GeoSeries(unselected_stops)

    # Convert the list of linestrings to a GeoDataFrame
    Z_lines = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry=Z_lines)

    # Plot the results
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))

        # Plot blocks
    blocks.plot(ax=ax, color='grey', markersize=5, label='Blocks', alpha=0.5)

    # Plot selected bus stops
    selected_stops.plot(ax=ax, color='blue', markersize=50, label='Selected Stops')

    # Plot unselected bus stops
    unselected_stops.plot(ax=ax, color='orange', markersize=50, label='Unselected Stops')

    # Plot assignment lines
    Z_lines.plot(ax=ax, color='grey', linewidth=1, label='Assignment Lines')

    # Add legend and title
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Model Output: Blocks and Bus Stops')
    plt.xlabel('Longitude')
    plt.ylabel('Latitude')

    # Show plot
    plt.show()
    
    return selected_stops, Z_lines, m.obj_val

Task: Recalculate the objective value, which represents the average travel distance.¶

  • Currently, the objective value indicates the total weighted distance, representing the total distance people living in the blocks will take to get to the assigned bus stops.
  • However, we want to obtain the average distance.
  • To achieve this, divide the total weighted distance by the total population of blocks.

Hint: Convert the objs list into a numpy array.
A numpy array divided by a constant number will return a new numpy array, where the original numpy array elements are divided by the constant number.

import geopandas as gpd

# Assuming selected_stops_4326 and unselected_stops_4326 are GeoSeries
selected_stops_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry=selected_stops_4326)
unselected_stops_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry=unselected_stops_4326)
blocks_4326 = blocks.to_crs(epsg=4326)

import folium

# Create a folium map
m = folium.Map(location=[blocks_4326.geometry.centroid.y.mean(), blocks_4326.geometry.centroid.x.mean()], zoom_start=12)

for idx, row in blocks_4326.iterrows():
    #Create circle markers for centroids of blocks with popup information
    folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[row.geometry.centroid.y, row.geometry.centroid.x],
        radius=3,
        popup= "Blocks",
        color='grey',
        fill_opacity=0.6,
        fill_color='gray'
        
    ).add_to(m)

# Plot selected stops
for idx, stop in selected_stops_gdf.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[stop.geometry.centroid.y, stop.geometry.centroid.x],
        radius=7,
        popup=f"Selected Stop {idx}",
        color='blue',
        fill_opacity=0.6,
        fill_color='blue'
    ).add_to(m)

# Plot unselected stops
for idx, stop in unselected_stops_gdf.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[stop.geometry.centroid.y, stop.geometry.centroid.x],
        radius=7,
        popup=f"Unselected Stop {idx}",
        color='orange',
        fill_opacity=0.6,
        fill_color='orange'
    ).add_to(m)

# Add assignment lines
for line in Z_lines_gdf_4326.geometry:
    folium.GeoJson(line, style_function=lambda x: {'color': 'gray', 'weight': 1}).add_to(m)


# Save the map to an HTML file
m.save("map.html")

Question 11: Explain why you picked the P value as the most desirable and discuss your findings from Lab 5. ( 2 pts )¶

Things you can discuss

  • [MUST]: Why you picked the P value as the most desirable.
  • [MUST]: How to interpret the model results according to P.
  • Estimate how much travel time will be reduced with your P number.
  • Insights from the model results.
  • Limitations of the model.
Put your ANSWER in this markdown cell¶

... Even though it is possible to accommodate all blocks with 42 bus stops, I decided that 46 bus stops is the most desireable when taking travel times into consideration. The scatterplot in question 9, and also attached below as a screenshot, shows that commute times exponentially decrease when adding bus stops within the range of 42 and 46 bus stops. However, after about 47 bus stops, the commute times plateau, and there isn't much of a difference even if you add bus stops. Therefore, I chose 46 bus stops so that we are still reducing the number of bus stop by 6 stops. This is likely to make the system more efficient and quick while also ensuring the bus stops are decently accessible to people walking from their homes.

... To interpret the model results according to P it is important to look at 'obj' which represents the travel distance from blocks to bus stops. The more bus stops there are, the shorter this average travel distance is because people living in different houses have more options. Therefore, there may be closer options available. As more bus stops are unselected, travel times increase. The model shows that we are still able to accomodate all blocks with 42 bus stops rather than the current 52 stops. However, with 42 bus stops, the average commute distance is about 250 meters rather than 235 meters (with 52 bus stops). With 46 bus stops, which is what I selected to be desirable, the average travel distance is 237.7m, reducing average distance by about 13 meters. This doesn't actually reduce travel time by that much, assuming that it takes about 5-15 seconds to walk 13 meters. The best objective, that the original model outputted, shows that with 42 bus stops, we are able to have a total weighted travel distance of about 8 million meters. This number decreases with 52 bus stops to 7.6 million meters. Therefore, the number of total meters travelled that reducing bus stops by 10 is about 400 thousand meters.

... Limitations of the model include technicalities that come with implementation. For example, it is unlikely that everybody will agree with the closing of certain bus stops, as there may be people who would be upset if a bus stop that's next to their house is removed, forcing them to walk a lot more every day. In addition, the model doesn't take ADA requirements into account, therefore, we don't know if the bus stop selection still allows access to people with transportation-related disabilities. Lastly, while the model does include block populations, it does not take into account the surroudning infrastructure around specific bus stops. For example, there is a hostpial near one of the bus stops that the model doesn't account for access to. In addition, the model doesn't take data about inflow and outflow of bus riders at each bus stop, which is a limitation.
